  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT135-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">talaimakaṉ piriyum eṉa vēṟupaṭṭa talaimakaṭkut tōḻi colliyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Uttered by the confidante to HER who had changed, saying “he is going to separate”.</p>
          </div>


        <div xml:id="KT135">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                viṉaiyē yāṭavark kuyirē vāṇutal</l>
<l>                maṉaiyuṟai makaḷirk kāṭava ruyireṉa</l>
<l>                namakkurait tōrun tāmē</l>
<l>                yaḻāa ṟōḻi yaḻuṅkuvar celavē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
           <l>“Work alone<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">viṉaiyē</term>: noticeable here the exclusive effect to be observed with <term xml:lang="ta">-ē</term> in anteposition; see also KT 174.6,7.</note> [is] life for men; for women</l>
           <l>with bright foreheads, staying at home, men [are] life.”</l>
           <l>[Thus] he himself too told us;</l>
           <l>don't cry, friend, he will refrain from going.</l>
            
                <lg type="alternate" sameAs="3+4b"><note place="foot">Or all the plurals have to be taken seriously, that is, several men are about to set out.</note>
                    <l>[so] also they themselves told us,</l>
                    <l>don't cry, friend, they will refrain from going.</l>
                </lg>
                <lg type="alternate" sameAs="3+4c"><note place="foot">Or the first two lines have to be read as an aphoristic prelude, subsequently contrasted with reality.</note>
                  <l>Even if they have told us: “...”,</l>
                  <l>don't cry, friend, he himself is one to give up going.</l>
                </lg>
           
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
